{{Merge|Keim's process|date=September 2018|discuss=Talk:Keim's process#Merge with Mineral_painting}} [[File:Emanuel Leutze - Westward the Course of Empire Takes Its Way - Capitol.jpg|thumb|[[Westward the Course of Empire Takes Its Way]] mural was made using '''stereochromy''' technique]] '''Mineral painting''' also known as '''Stereochromy''' is a [[mural]] painting technique that uses a [[water glass]] based paint.
The original technique was called Stereochromy where [[pigment]]s were applied to [[plaster]] or stone and sealed with [[water glass]] to preserve and enhance the colors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Westward the Course of Empire Takes Its Way |url=https://www.aoc.gov/art/other-paintings-and-murals/westward-course-empire-takes-its-way |website=Architect of the Capitol {{!}} United States Capitol |accessdate=30 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stereochromy - definition, etymology and usage, examples and related words |url=http://www.finedictionary.com/Stereochromy.html |website=www.finedictionary.com |accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref> The name was first used about 1825 by [[Johann Nepomuk von Fuchs]] and Schlotthaurer,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Doerner |first1=Max |title=The Materials of the Artist and Their Use in Painting: With Notes on the Techniques of the Old Masters, Revised Edition |date=1984 |publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich |isbn=9780156577168 |edition= First |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Spcd1-cZpsMC&pg=PA311&lpg=PA311&dq=J.+Fuchs+and+Schlotthaurer&source=bl&ots=T8ZbiEjEbV&sig=fNDXBjOb4yNy0Um3C2v1sJtyzgY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjJ3P-z9pTdAhVIWq0KHQKOBW0Q6AEwBHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=J.%20Fuchs%20and%20Schlotthaurer&f=false |language=English|page=311}}</ref> but then improved in the 1880's by [[Adolf Wilhelm Keim]] and renamed as ''mineral painting''<ref name=CAMEO >{{cite web |title=Mineral painting - CAMEO |url=http://cameo.mfa.org/wiki/Mineral_painting |website=cameo.mfa.org |accessdate=30 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>Mayer, Ralph. ''A Dictionary of Art Terms and Techniques'', Harper and Row Publishers, New York, 1969</ref> or [[Keim's process]].
